  "prompt": "What were the major events of Spain in 1492?",
  "response": "The year 1492 was pivotal in Spanish history and marked by several major events:\n\n1. **Completion of the Reconquista**: In January 1492, the Catholic Monarchs, Queen Isabella I of Castile and King Ferdinand II of Aragon, completed the Reconquista with the capture of Granada. This event ended centuries of Muslim rule on the Iberian Peninsula and united Spain under Christian rule.\n\n2. **Expulsion of the Jews**: On March 31, 1492, the Alhambra Decree (also known as the Edict of Expulsion) was issued by the Catholic Monarchs, ordering the expulsion of practicing Jews from the Kingdoms of Castile and Aragon by the end of July unless they converted to Christianity. This event led to a significant migration of Jewish communities to other parts of Europe and the Ottoman Empire.\n\n3. **Columbus's First Voyage**: On August 3, 1492, Christopher Columbus set sail from Spain on his first voyage across the Atlantic Ocean, under the patronage of the Catholic Monarchs. This voyage culminated in the discovery of the Americas on October 12, 1492, when Columbus landed in the Bahamas, marking the beginning of the Spanish colonization of the New World and a significant moment in world history.\n\nThese events had profound and lasting impacts on Spain and the world, influencing everything from cultural dynamics and religious landscapes to global trade and exploration.",
